[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating reflection in tests**\n\nI'm pondering if using reflection in testing is actually prohibited. The guideline suggests not to use it directly unless the public API really needs it. The ClassMap's API returns a Method, which seems necessary for verifying behavior. While invoking through Method feels natural, maybe I can avoid it by asserting the class name and parameters instead. Still, I wonder if behavioral assertions alone would suffice. It's all a bit confusing!\n\n**Verifying JDK knowledge**\n\nI'm checking my understanding of the JDK, particularly that getMethods returns all public methods from a class or interface, including inherited ones. Even if a class is non-public, it will still return public methods. I also note how ClassMap.getPublicMethod interacts with private classes and retrieves public members. Furthermore, I consider whether to add metadata and if tests for exercising ClassMap should reflect configurations for test classes. Lastly, I wonder if the native image needs to account for methods.\n\n**Checking reflection metadata**\n\nI’m considering how the method on test classes interacts with native images that require reflection metadata. It seems like the agent could produce the necessary test metadata. But hold on, I notice there isn’t a src/test/resources directory to draw from? I should double-check and clarify how the metadata is being handled and whether it’s being generated properly for those classes. It’s essential to ensure everything is set up correctly!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09236850308d92d20169f0658a1cb0819d97dcfe2b4f41c209\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8GWcMyvTxegWdCFJWsxI2GWK3k8nlZpf4TZ4zLo6AxoOGx0g8YQVSr5PKSTEORm2zpTFMmmpX2xDbq7fvSq1-pV8ciTxj9zFp9k7mVj3-4tPNAFXm1WOVpYgazrJ_ZO--i26jzypWvvdN9IWphFaFJa-xiMMmk4XVG6T7Nko0jj2teGYObUtPZjxenPIzTtE4OHFdk2BgvejeNH4YFAq1uS1t2vmLk8RdL-Z